title: For Sale:  1886 Bullard Large Frame Deluxe Lever Action Rifle ANTIQUE Pistol Grip 45-70 High Cond. Special Order
postcontent: Dave mark Trading is one of the most experienced dealers of fine antique arms, with over 30 years of collecting. We also specialize in a vast array of collectibles, including western memorabilia, antique cars & automobilia, Revolutionary & Civil War relics, early Bowie & folding knives, and period nautical artifacts. ~ Very Rare, High Condition M1886 Bullard Large Frame Deluxe Lever Action Rifle with Checkered Pistol Grip, Special Length Barrel, and Half Magazine, .45-70, mfg. 1886-1890. Bullard rifles were the finest repeating rifles of their day and a top competitor to the Winchester Repeating Arms Company. They were only produced for a brief period of time and Deluxe models, such as this one, are seldom encountered. This example is all original top to bottom and remains in very high condition. The special order 25" octagon barrel features a standard rifle front sight and adjustable semi buckhorn rear. The barrel and magazine tube retain approximately 90%+ bright original bluing with only slight freckling beginning. The receiver, hammer, lever, and forend cap retain 85% vivid case color with the balance having just faded to silver. The stock is beautifully figured Deluxe grade wood featuring a checkered pistol grip and forearm. It should be noted that not all Deluxe Bullards had extra fancy wood and it is quite rare to see wood of this grade. A coat of varnish has been applied to the buttstock only which has crazed with age. It must have been wrapped in cloth for sometime after as there is a slight imprint made in the varnish. It should be easy enough to remove the finish and reveal the original surface underneath but we will leave that to the next owner. Otherwise the forestock retains it's untouched original finish. The wood has never been sanded or cleaned and shows tight, perfect wood to metal fit throughout with sharp original checkering. The toe of the buttstock has been rounded slightly, and a chip has been repaired on the tip of the pistol grip utilizing the original piece. Original Bullard hard rubber buttplate shows little to no wear with slight rounding at the base. Lower tang and rear sight still retain vivid fire bluing. Clear Bullard Repeating Arms Company address, serial number, and top of frame marked "Cal 45 70". All clean, original screws throughout. The action is crisp and functions flawlessly. These guns were actually very well known for their amazingly smooth action. The bore is absolutely flawless with perfectly clean and sharp rifling front to back. Not even a hint of frosting. Bullard rifles were actually better quality, particularly in design, than Winchester however they just couldn't keep up with the competition. If you've been looking to get your hands on a truly spectacular, high condition Deluxe Bullard look no further. These do not turn up often. Not to mention this one is chambered in one of the most sought after calibers! No FFL required on pre-1899 firearms or contemporary muzzleloaders. title: For Sale:  Real Colt Dragoon 2nd Gen  Percussion
postcontent: LET'S STOP KIDDING OURSELVES about 2nd and 3rd generation Colt percussion pistols being "collectible". I have been involved with percussion weapons since well before Colt got the bright idea to remake these guns in the early seventies. They started this production strictly to capitalize on both the renewed interest in Old West type guns AND the increasing value of original antique weapons of this type. They did this against a background of the IRS at the time allowing for the investment of IRA retirement funds in what were referred to as 'hard assets' as well as stocks, bonds, and other conventional investment mediums. In real terms that meant that each year a tax payer could put as much as $4000 into things like collector coins, art, and even guns and deduct it from gross income. A neat idea, and this"hard asset" provision drove the demand for guns crazy at the time. Unless you're sixty-five or seventy years old you're not likely to remember this. So Colt started selling these guns as "collector items" and the market responded by thinking that they would be a great investment as they would undoubtedly go way, way up in value. Hah! I was only 23 in the early seventies and didn't know any better. But I soon learned. In the 1980's the IRS disallowed IRA investment in hard assets, and gun demand softened up. There were thousands of idiots who, like myself, bought an early production new in the box Colt Navy for $400 or so - thirty-five or forty years ago. I say idiots, because virtually none of us at the time ever thought these guns, whether a C series or an F series would NOT go up in value as time went by. Well, forty years later, they haven't, despite gun gougers trying to get eight or nine hundred dollars for them on gunbroker, gunsamerica, and elsewhere. When they actually DO sell, it's usually for five or six hundred dollars, or even less, which is one hell of a crappy increase in value for something that sold for $400 in the seventies or eighties. Despite Colt's marketing b.s. at the time, these were NOT legitimate "collector items" back then, nor are they collector items today. And unknown to virtually all buyers at the time was the hard fact that since Colt was selling these things as "keep it in the box, keep it unfired, keep it unturned" "collectorItems" few realized that these guns VERY often would not function properly if one tried to actually shoot them. I have defarbed several of these guns and the problems are usually connected to the wedge having never been correctly fitted and the cylinder will not properly headspace against the breech of the barrel. That means that the hammer will not hit each nipple hard enough to fire a cap. Right out of the box some wedges are barely even driven all the way through the frame at all. And driving it in properly will cause the barrel breech to bind up on the cylinder face and jam the action. And for some odd reason, nipples on the various models are not of uniform size. About a third of the time nipples must be removed and turned down to properly accommodate a cap. Since these "investment items" were not meant to ever be fired Colt apparently didn't attend well to good functional fit. Remember, these precious things were meant to be kept boxed up forever, so few owners would ever realize this. Since Uberti percussion pistols were made to be used, the fit and function is much more reliable. This particular Colt 2nd generation WORKS AS IT SHOULD and looks good. I'm selling it for $400 for the gun and $225 for the work on it. It too, is NOT A COLLECTOR ITEM! It is however, a good shooter. Don't be buffalo'd by gun gougers high dollar "collectibility' b.s. about a pistol being 'new unturned' Buying these guns, including this one, will likely result in a net loss of value over a period of years. An inflation chart shows that 400 1975 dollars would be worth $1781 in 2017. A $400 gun bought in 1975 SHOULD be worth nearly $1800 today, which would be a value gain of four and half times. That sure as hell hasn't worked out that way for these great "collector items". Buy one of these to shoot, not to "invest" in. This is how I see it after fifty years.  $15 shipping.

title: For Sale:  1953 Argentine Sistema Model 1927
postcontent: For Sale or Layaway:  Colt Argentine Sistema Model 1927 1911 converted to 22LR trainer for Police Depts by Marcati.  As the Argentina government transitioned to Browning Hi-Power pistols, many out-of-service Colt Sistema 1911s were converted to 22LR for training purposes.  This pistol uses the floating chamber barrel design, has been test fired and functions properly.  The design is based off of the Colt Ace since the Sistemas are, in all aspects of quality/manufacturing, a Colt 1911.  Argentina purchased Colt 1911 drawings and manufacturing rights in 20s/30s.  With Colt techicians and West German equipment, started producing Sistemas from 1945-1966.  These are very fine and affordable examples of the Colt M1911A1s.  The 22LR trainer conversions were done by two companies, Venturini and Macarti.  Both did quality work with Venturini completing a high number of conversions.
